  "stem": "<p>The current <em>I</em> in a circuit is given by <math><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math>, where <em>V</em> is the voltage and <em>R</em> is the resistance. Which of the following correctly expresses <em>V</em> in terms of <em>I</em> and <em>R</em>?</p>",
  "answerOptions": [
    {
      "id": "a",
      "content": "<p><math><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>I</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math></p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "b",
      "content": "<p><math><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>R</mi></math></p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "c",
      "content": "<p><math><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>R</mi><mi>I</mi></mfrac></math></p>"
    },
    {
      "id": "d",
      "content": "<p><math><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>R</mi></math></p>"
    }
  ],
  "keys": [
    "d"
  ],
  "rationale": "<p>Choice D is correct. Multiplying both sides of <math><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>V</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math> by <em>R</em> yields <math><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>I</mi><mi>R</mi></math>.</p><p>Choices A, B, and C are incorrect.</p>",
